[2026-03-13T18:36:12Z] [llm] {"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-opus-4-6","id":"msg_0167uk8ok7FQBbeVRtSn9qCZ","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"text","text":"All tests pass. Here's a summary of the changes:\n\n**Root cause:** The container cleanup had three issues:\n\n1. **`docker rm` without `-f` flag** (`internal/adapters/docker/runtime.go`): The `Remove` method used `docker rm` without the `-f` (force) flag, while other cleanup calls in the same file used `docker rm -f`. Without `-f`, removal fails for containers in certain states (dead, paused, etc.), and the error was silently collected but never displayed to the user.\n\n2. **Running containers were skipped** (`internal/adapters/web/handler.go`): The cleanup handlers skipped running containers entirely instead of stopping them first. If a container was still running when cleanup was triggered, it would be silently skipped and remain.\n\n3. **Ignored `UpdateRun` error**: In the \"container already gone\" path, the `UpdateRun` error was ignored while still incrementing the `deleted` count, causing the response to report success while the database flag remained unchanged.\n\n**Fixes:**\n- `docker/runtime.go`: Added `-f` flag to `docker rm` in `Remove()`\n- `web/handler.go`: Extracted shared cleanup logic into `removeContainers()` method that:\n  - Stops running containers before removing them (instead of skipping)\n  - Properly handles `UpdateRun` errors in all paths\n- Updated tests to verify running containers are stopped then removed\n\nCLOCHE_RESULT:success"}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":1,"cache_creation_input_tokens":818,"cache_read_input_tokens":98398,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":818},"output_tokens":1,"service_tier":"standard","inference_geo":"not_available"},"context_management":null},"parent_tool_use_id":null,"session_id":"8afa4431-c2af-45d7-8651-174f88b0e5d9","uuid":"1ba97390-c9be-48b1-b